  "prompt": "Do anions have a larger radius than neutral atoms?",
  "response": "Generally, anions have a larger atomic radius compared to their neutral atom counterparts. This is because when an atom gains one or more electrons, the increased electron repulsion causes the electron cloud to expand, resulting in a larger overall atomic radius. \n\nKey points:\n1. Electron addition increases electron-electron repulsion\n2. This leads to greater electron cloud expansion\n3. Results in a larger ionic radius\n4. The increase in size can be significant, typically 30-50% larger than the neutral atom\n\nFor example:\n- Neutral sodium atom (Na): smaller radius\n- Sodium anion (Na\u207b): larger radius\n\nThe magnitude of size increase depends on factors like:\n- Number of electrons added\n- Electron shell configuration\n- Atomic structure\n\nThe trend is consistent across most elements in the periodic table, with some minor variations based on specific electronic configurations.",
